text.html: Dojo Has it Large on... Kingsland Road
text.text: Dojo Has it Large on... Kingsland Road

Beards, rustic clothes, copious ale drinking. No, this isn’t Game of Thrones and we haven’t been snooping for hangouts in King’s Landing, but the wild strip of Kingsland Road has popped up on our compass this time round. What’s all the fuss about? We’ll see: get your helmets and shin pads on, folks, it’s time to have it large.
Best for… coffee inna da sun

tip.text:
Initially conceived as a workspace for creatives, Curio Cabal has come on leaps and bounds to become one of Kingsland Road's coolest spots for a coffee. The seating area out front is pure bliss when the sun's out and Jeremy's even looking to install a fish tank wall inside(!).

Get down for great coffee and delish breakfast-y and brunch-y bites: the Cabal breakfast features scrambled eggs, chorizo, hash browns, beans and mushrooms. What else? Home-cured Salmon, super fresh and healthy smoothies, coffee-based cocktails and bread from E5.

text.text: The seating area out front here is absolutely The Shit; a delightful spot for catching rays and getting your coffee on out on the Kingsland Road. Speak to Jeremy, he’s a charming and ambitious chap dishing out simple and tasty breakfasts to hungry Hackney-ites. Pop into Curio in the evening for some Chinese inspired small plates by Ta Ta.
Best for... healthy brunching

tip.text:
There are two kinds of brunches in our book: the indulgent kind and the healthy, wholesome kind. It can be pretty tricky to find a place that manages to do both, which is part of what makes Hara well worth a visit. Owners Kiara and Tess create nourishing and super-delicious brunch eats that hit all the pleasure spots whilst also providing something colourful and healthy for the 'gram. Feelings of smugness are guaranteed.

On a short menu, we went for the popular 'Socca', coming with beetroot polpette, red kraut, herb hummus, purple sprouting broccoli and a soft boiled egg. It looked good, it tasted real good. Shout out to the sweet-tooth satisfying French Toast, too. Watch out for fermentation workshops, supper clubs and other holistic events happening as well - these guys have their fingers in all kinds of good-living pies.

tip.text:
Sweetie, darling, stop flouncing around shitty pubs and head over to Haggerston. The Glory may look like your average East End boozer, complete with an ebony bar, friendly wine-drinkers and chilled-out tuneage, but once you make your way downstairs, it's an entirely different picture.

Expect to see the Glory's infamous co-owners, John Sizzle and Jonny Woo, grace the basement's stage with their presence, along with a plethora of London's alternative cabaret performers, camp DJs, thought-provoking pieces and outlandish performance artists. The Glory wanted to forge a home for London's incredibly diverse and talented queer counterculture, and they've done a damn good job of it.

tip.text:
Carl Clarke, aka the chef turned DJ behind God Save the Clam, Rock Lobsta and Disco Bistro is famous for his burgers and seafood. Now he's turning his hand to fried chicken and wait for it...sour cocktails.

This unlikely combination is the perfect answer to those late night cravings. We'd recommend starting off with a little szechuan aubergine, then working your way through the crispiest, tastiest chicken in town. Big dogs will be tempted to order the whole fried chicken but smaller bites are just as good especially when paired with zingers like ginger miso slaw, pickled watermelon or hot-and-sour pineapple. And to drink? Sours of course!

tip.text:
Tucked in between brighter, louder restaurants on Kingsland Road, Three Sheets is easy to walk right past. This dimly lit watering hole is short on space but makes up for it by oozing atmosphere with a white-marble bar and a single row of two-seater high tables, just begging to be the backdrop for a hot date or a moody, solitary cocktail.

Serving Alchemy coffee, light snacks, and a weekly rotating menu of inventive, seasonal cocktails, this inconspicuous neighbourhood bar can certainly hold its own in terms of quality. It's owned by two lovely Northern lads (catch them behind the bar, always ready to engage in pleasant chatter), one of whom gained his stripes working at Tony Conigliaro’s Drink Factory, where cocktails are developed for some of London's best bars. A little spot with a lot of love - we'll raise a well-mixed drink to that.

tip.text:
While you're definitely spoilt for choice with Vietnamese food on this strip of Kingsland Road, this sweet, family run restaurant might just be the pick of the bunch. Hanoi Cafe has by far the most welcoming interior: the left-side walls are lined with colourful, post-war propaganda posters from the nation, while the right-side boasts stunning black and white photos of the family.

Don't know what to eat? Everything in here is made with lovely, fresh ingredients and dishes are packed full of flavour and a pinch of spice. Light and tasty summer rolls; authentic 'bun' vermicelli noodle salads; and crunchy baguettes, packed with grilled pork and veg, all make deciding difficult. Your problem, not ours. The £6 lunch deal is an absolute no brainer.

text.text: One of the first Vietnamese eateries to set-up shop on this stretch of Kingsland Road, the charming and hospitable family that run Hanoi Cafe departed their homeland by boat in 1980. What they’ve been kind enough to give us Londoners is an authentic slice of Vietnam: unreasonably tasty food at great value, prepared with all the heart that goes into true home cooking. Admire the beauty of the colourful, post-war propaganda posters flanking the left wall.
Best for… all that jazz

tip.text:
LDN’s not blessed with many spots with the attention to detail of Tokyo's listening bars, but Brilliant Corners comes damn close. This dimly lit haven is built on quality with exquisite food, drink and sound combining to create a potent mixture that lures locals in for date-night cocktails, and keeps them a little later than they planned to tuck into some sumptuous (and fairly priced) sushi. Before you know it, you've been enveloped in a hypnotic cloak of sound as the hi-grade speakers take centre stage.

You really wanna be here come midnight, when the tables get moved to the side and the moon-like orbs provide the only illumination for a sensory shakedown to jazz, rare groove, house or soul. A rarefied taste of things done right.

text.text: Your senses have carried you this far in life and we reckon it’s apt to treat them. This one’s for all you ears and mouths out there (we see you!). Peep the fucking incredible sound system here. Listen to vinyl spin and experience the depth and beauty of analog sound; sip on a negroni (cos you deserve that) and tuck into some yum Japanese food. This spot is so real, yo.
Best for... cocktails and kimchee somewhere atmospheric

tip.text:
If Blade Runner was set in Seoul, this is just the kind of slick, stripped-back cocktail joint where the protagonist would roll in for a moody cocktail in the early hours right before a crazy action set piece. Set up by James Shepherd (hence Shep’s), this is a well-executed escapist operation: Korean-inspired cocktails and rich, liquor-friendly food to accompany it, from a narrow space kitted out with parquet flooring, mesmerising orbs of light and swish black-leather seats.

The innovative cocktail list changes every month and is typically five drinks strong - inspired by Korea and whatever spirit is tickling the owner’s pickle. Talking of pickles, they feature on a menu of delicious comfort grub: bits like kimchi fried rice, dashi braised mushrooms and smoked pork jowl. Nestling into a booth with a date after dark is like a trip to a strange and alluring place and we dig it.

Best for... a cheap vegan eat

tip.text:
Is the rapid spread of the 'small, sharing plates' trend doing your nut in? Well what better way to revolt than by getting rid of plates all together? Andu is the perfect spot to do so - this Kingsland Road gem is one of those no-bullshit places that serves up simple and delicious Ethiopian food which also happens to be 100% vegan. It's BYOB, the staff are bloody lovely and it’s damn cheap to boot. And as is the way with Ethiopian cuisine, the food is served atop injera bread (sour fermented pancake).

We’d recommend grabbing a pal and rolling down to Dalston to try the ‘sampler’, a selection of six dishes served atop injera or rice - perfect for two to share and yours for only £12. If you’re in the area and dining Han Solo, you can get an individual sampler to take away for a fiver. So leave any vibe-snipers at home and get yourself down to Andu before you can say “yemisir wot” (Ethiopian red lentil stew).

Best for... culture in the community

tip.text:
Remember when little orphan Annie with her red curly hair went to the cinema with Mr Warbucks, and it just looked sick, with all that luxe decor and red velour seating. Well, Rio Cinema is kinda like that. This Grade II listed Art Deco building is home to a 1930s auditorium that's got some seriously sweepin' curves, red velvet seats, atmospheric pre-show music and long red curtains that swish back before the film starts.

With all these bougie adjectives, you'd be forgiven for thinking this was some high-end, money grabbing machine. But oh how wrong you are honey. Rio Cinema is London's longest operating community cinema, having been not-for-profit for the last 40 years. In upkeep with its community vibes, they play host to educational school screenings, fundraising events and various films festivals.

tip.text:
Mangal 1 is proof that the holy kebab is not solely reserved for drunken gluttony. This ocakbasi is a king among London's many kebab houses, and maybe the best is Dalston (which is saying something). Nudge your way past the people waiting by the door for takeaway, past the gargantuan, smoking grill and find a table in the crowded dining room.

Service is brusque at best, but you're here for food, not service, so grab the attention of a waiter and order up. Starters are tasty but unnecessary - the grill is where it's at. Ideally you're in a group large enough to warrant a big platter where you can sample a range of perfectly grilled meats. If you're riding solo, go for the lamb chops. Either way you'll get fluffy, warm bread, salads and some sauces. It's byob, so run over the road for beers and then get stuck into your meat feast. Just leave some room for the hella syrupy baklava, ok?
